\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>|b|$
\end_inset

.
 By absolute value definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|b|\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $|b|=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>0$
\end_inset

 (Because 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>|b|$
\end_inset

), thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|b|\cdot|b|=0$
\end_inset

 (According to 1.30.2), thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|\cdot|a|=a^{2}$
\end_inset

, and according to 1.41 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}>b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $|b|>0$
\end_inset

 then also 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>0$
\end_inset

 (Due to 1.35.2), and by theorem 1.39 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|\cdot|a|>|b|\cdot|b|$
